    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm working on an embedded project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow RAM exhaustion over about 4-6 hours of continuous operation. i've looked at the main loop and can't see any obvious missing deletes, but it's definitely leaking something. can you give me a systematic approach for finding where the leak is happening in a C++ environment like this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Start by adding a custom heap allocator that tracks every allocation and deallocation with precise timestamps and stack traces, then monitor this data to identify which specific function is responsible for the leak. Since C++ dynamic memory management is complex, use a tool like Valgrind or AddressSanitizer to pinpoint the exact location of the memory failure in your codebase. Once you have the suspicious function, carefully inspect how objects are destroyed and ensure that all dynamic memory is properly freed before the next allocation cycle.",
